ley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England"},"cs":{"1420–1461":"1420–1461","1437–1466":"1437–1466","1420–1509":"1420–1509","1445–1509":"1445–1509","1446–1527":"1446–1527","1409–1475":"1409–1475","1400–1512":"1400–1512","1461":"1461","1437":"1437","1446":"1446","1512":"1512","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","about 1445":"okolo 1445","1509":"1509","1409":"1409","1527":"1527","England":"Anglie","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, Anglie"},"da":{"1420–1461":"1420–1461","1437–1466":"1437–1466","1420–1509":"1420–1509","1445–1509":"1445–1509","1446–1527":"1446–1527","1409–1475":"1409–1475","1400–1512":"1400–1512","1461":"1461","1437":"1437","1446":"1446","1512":"1512","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","about 1445":"omkring 1445","1509":"1509","1409":"1409","1527":"1527","England":"England","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England"},"nl":{"1420–1461":"1420–1461","1437–1466":"1437–1466","1420–1509":"1420–1509","1445–1509":"1445–1509","1446–1527":"1446–1527","1409–1475":"1409–1475","1400–1512":"1400–1512","1461":"1461","1437":"1437","1446":"1446","1512":"1512","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","about 1445":"circa 1445","1509":"1509","1409":"1409","1527":"1527","England":"England","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England"},"en":{"1420–1461":"1420–1461","1437–1466":"1437–1466","1420–1509":"1420–1509","1445–1509":"1445–1509","1446–1527":"1446–1527","1409–1475":"1409–1475","1400–1512":"1400–1512","1461":"1461","1437":"1437","1446":"1446","1512":"1512","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","about 1445":"about 1445","1509":"1509","1409":"1409","1527":"1527","England":"England","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Walker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly North and Midlands) and Scottish: occupational name for a fuller, from Middle English <i>walker</i>, Old English <i>wealcere</i> (an agent derivative of <i>wealcan</i> ‘to walk, tread’), ‘one who trampled cloth in a bath of lye or kneaded it, in order to strengthen it’. This was the regular term for the occupation during the Middle Ages in western and northern England. Compare   Fuller   and   Tucker  . As a Scottish surname it has also been used as a translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an Fhucadair</b> ‘son of the fuller’. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","History: The name was brought to North America from northern England and Scotland independently by many different bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. Samuel Walker came to Lynn, MA, <i>c.</i> 1630; Philip Walker was in Rehoboth, MA, in or before 1643. The surname was also established in VA before 1650; a Thomas Walker, born in 1715 in King and Queen County, VA, was a physician, soldier, and explorer."],"variants":[{"name":"Walcher","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gunther, Hans, Horst, Klaus.","German: variant of   Walker   or   Walch  ."]},{"name":"Waker","meanings":["English (Yorkshire):","either a nickname for a watchful person or an occupational name for a watchman, from Middle English <i>waker</i> ‘watchful, vigilant’ (Old English <i>wacor</i>) and the derived noun.","mostly an early Modern English and Scots variant of   Walker  ."]},{"name":"Fuller","meanings":["English: occupational name for a dresser of cloth, from Middle English <i>fuller</i> ‘fuller of cloth’ (partly from Old English <i>fullere</i>, partly from Old French <i>fouleor</i>, <i>foleur</i>, Latin <i>fullo</i>). Raw cloth had to be fulled, i.e. scoured, cleansed, and thickened by beating or trampling it in water, a process also known as <i>walking</i> or <i>tucking</i>, hence the surnames   Walker   and   Tucker   alongside <i>Fuller</i>. These three terms and surnames are characteristic of different parts of England. In general, in Middle English, <i>Fuller</i> is southern and eastern, while <i>Walker</i> belongs to the west and north and <i>Tucker</i> is southwestern. Compare   Fullen  .","English: variant of   Fullard   with loss of <i>-d</i>.","German (<b>Füller</b>): occupational name for a person whose work involved filling, such as a dauber, or a nickname for a gourmand or glutton. Compare   Filler  ."]},{"name":"Walke","meanings":["German: metonymic occupational name for a fuller, from Middle High German <i>walke</i> ‘fulling mill’. Compare   Walker  .","English (Devon): variant of   Walk  ."]},{"name":"Walck","meanings":["German: variant of   Walker   or   Walch  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Alice Walker was born in 1420, in England, her father, William Walker, was 11 and her mother, Ealifia Walker (m), was 20. She had at least 2 daughters with John William Burr Bures II, of Brenchley. She died in 1461, in her hometown, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1420–1461":"1420–1461","1437–1466":"1437–1466","1420–1509":"1420–1509","1445–1509":"1445–1509","1446–1527":"1446–1527","1409–1475":"1409–1475","1400–1512":"1400–1512","1461":"1461","1437":"1437","1446":"1446","1512":"1512","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","about 1445":"umbes 1445","1509":"1509","1409":"1409","1527":"1527","England":"England","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1420–1461":"1420–1461","1437–1466":"1437–1466","1420–1509":"1420–1509","1445–1509":"1445–1509","1446–1527":"1446–1527","1409–1475":"1409–1475","1400–1512":"1400–1512","1461":"1461","1437":"1437","1446":"1446","1512":"1512","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","about 1445":"noin 1445","1509":"1509","1409":"1409","1527":"1527","England":"England","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England"},"fr":{"1420–1461":"1420–1461","1437–1466":"1437–1466","1420–1509":"1420–1509","1445–1509":"1445–1509","1446–1527":"1446–1527","1409–1475":"1409–1475","1400–1512":"1400–1512","1461":"1461","1437":"1437","1446":"1446","1512":"1512","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","about 1445":"environ 1445","1509":"1509","1409":"1409","1527":"1527","England":"Angleterre","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Lady Alice Walker est née en 1420, à Angleterre, son père, William Walker, avait 11 ans et sa mère, Ea